{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GuQeiy9GLCA4d9WzZ8rTc9","type":"tool_result","content":"apiVersion: v1\nitems:\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    plan.md: |\n      # Ray Cluster Change / Migration Plan\n      ## Review Date: 2026-06-23\n      ## Status: DRAFT — NO CHANGES APPLIED\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 1. Current Cluster State\n\n      ### Namespace\n      - **Namespace:** `ray`\n\n      ### Deployments\n\n      | Deployment   | Replicas | Image                    | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |\n      |-------------|----------|--------------------------|-------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|\n      | ray-head    | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0     | (none)      | (none)    | (none)         | (none)       |\n      | ray-worker  | 3        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0     | (none)      | (none)    | (none)         | (none)       |\n\n      ### Service: ray-head (ClusterIP)\n\n      | Port Name | Port  | Target Port | Protocol |\n      |-----------|-------|-------------|----------|\n      | gcs       | 6379  | 6379        | TCP      |\n      | dashboard | 8265  | 8265        | TCP      |\n      | client    | 10001 | 10001       | TCP      |\n\n      The dashboard port (8265) is exposed on the ClusterIP service — this is a\n      non-default addition beyond the minimal GCS port required for cluster operation.\n\n      ### Notable Observations\n      - Neither deployment has resource requests or limits set (`resources: {}`).\n        This means the pods are BestEffort QoS class and can be OOM-killed under\n        node pressure without warning.\n      - The cluster runs Ray 2.9.0, which is multiple minor versions behind the\n        current stable series.\n      - Workers were scaled from the default of 1 to 3 replicas, providing more\n        parallel task capacity.\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 2. Proposed Changes for the Next Upgrade Window\n\n      ### 2a. Image Upgrade: 2.9.0 → 2.10.0\n\n      Upgrade both head and worker deployments to `rayproject/ray:2.10.0`.\n      This is a minor-version bump, preserving API compatibility while picking up\n      bug fixes and performance improvements in the GCS, Dashboard, and runtime.\n\n      **Risk:** Low. Both deployments are updated in sequence (head first, then\n      workers) so that the head node is stable before workers reconnect.\n\n      ### 2b. Add Resource Requests and Limits\n\n      Set explicit CPU and memory requests/limits on both deployments to move them\n      from BestEffort to Guaranteed QoS. Proposed values based on Ray's recommended\n      minimums for a dev/staging cluster:\n\n      | Deployment  | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |\n      |------------|-------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|\n      | ray-head   | 500m        | 1000m     | 512Mi          | 1Gi          |\n      | ray-worker | 500m        | 2000m     | 1Gi            | 2Gi          |\n\n      Tune these values against observed usage from `kubectl top pods -n ray`\n      before the window opens.\n\n      ### 2c. Scale Workers from 3 → 4 Replicas\n\n      Add a fourth worker replica to increase the cluster's parallel task throughput\n      and provide headroom during rolling restarts (at least 3 workers available at\n      any time with `maxUnavailable=1`).\n\n      ### 2d. Evaluate Dashboard Exposure\n\n      The dashboard (8265) is currently reachable only within the cluster via\n      ClusterIP. If team members need browser access during the upgrade window,\n      consider temporarily creating a NodePort or port-forwarding session rather\n      than changing the Service type permanently. No Service-type change is\n      proposed in this plan; it is recorded here for discussion.\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 3. Proposed Change Order\n\n      1. Verify cluster health and note current metrics.\n      2. Apply resource requests/limits to ray-head (triggers rolling restart of 1 pod).\n      3. Confirm ray-head pod is Running and dashboard is reachable.\n      4. Apply resource requests/limits to ray-worker (rolling restart, maxUnavailable=1).\n      5. Upgrade ray-head image to 2.10.0 (triggers rolling restart).\n      6. Confirm ray-head reconnects and cluster is healthy.\n      7. Upgrade ray-worker image to 2.10.0 (rolling restart).\n      8. Scale ray-worker from 3 → 4 replicas.\n      9. Run a smoke-test job to confirm task submission succeeds.\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 4. Exact kubectl Commands (DO NOT RUN — for review only)\n\n      ### Step 1 — Snapshot current state\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray get deploy ray-head ray-worker -o yaml > /tmp/ray-pre-upgrade-snapshot.yaml\n      kubectl -n ray get svc ray-head -o yaml >> /tmp/ray-pre-upgrade-snapshot.yaml\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 2 — Add resource requests/limits to ray-head\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray set resources deployment/ray-head   --requests=cpu=500m,memory=512Mi   --limits=cpu=1000m,memory=1Gi\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 3 — Add resource requests/limits to ray-worker\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray set resources deployment/ray-worker   --requests=cpu=500m,memory=1Gi   --limits=cpu=2000m,memory=2Gi\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 4 — Upgrade ray-head image\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray set image deployment/ray-head   ray-head=rayproject/ray:2.10.0\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-head --timeout=120s\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 5 — Upgrade ray-worker image\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray set image deployment/ray-worker   ray-worker=rayproject/ray:2.10.0\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker --timeout=180s\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 6 — Scale workers to 4 replicas\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray scale deployment/ray-worker --replicas=4\n      kubectl -n ray rollout status deployment/ray-worker --timeout=60s\n      ```\n\n      ### Step 7 — Verify post-upgrade state\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray get pods -o wide\n      kubectl -n ray get deploy ray-head ray-worker   -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{\" replicas=\"}{.spec.replicas}{\" image=\"}{.spec.template.spec.containers[0].image}{\"\\n\"}{end}'\n      ```\n\n      ### Rollback (if needed)\n      ```bash\n      kubectl -n ray rollout undo deployment/ray-head\n      kubectl -n ray rollout undo deployment/ray-worker\n      kubectl -n ray scale deployment/ray-worker --replicas=3\n      ```\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 5. Sign-off Checklist\n\n      - [ ] Plan reviewed by on-call engineer\n      - [ ] Maintenance window scheduled and communicated\n      - [ ] Pre-upgrade snapshot taken (`/tmp/ray-pre-upgrade-snapshot.yaml`)\n      - [ ] Node resource headroom confirmed (`kubectl top nodes`)\n      - [ ] Smoke-test job ready to run post-upgrade\n  kind: ConfigMap\n  metadata:\n    creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-23T21:35:47Z\"\n    name: change-plan\n    namespace: ray\n    resourceVersion: \"915054\"\n    uid: 73a4b3ae-8e87-47c9-b9f2-ea3b4fdcd1ee\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    job.py: |\n      import ray\n\n      ray.init(address=\"ray://ray-head:10001\")\n\n      print(\"pong\")\n\n      ray.shutdown()\n  kind: ConfigMap\n  metadata:\n    annotations:\n      kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration: |\n        {\"apiVersion\":\"v1\",\"data\":{\"job.py\":\"import ray\\n\\nray.init(address=\\\"ray://ray-head:10001\\\")\\n\\nprint(\\\"pong\\\")\\n\\nray.shutdown()\\n\"},\"kind\":\"ConfigMap\",\"metadata\":{\"annotations\":{},\"labels\":{\"app.kubernetes.io/component\":\"job-script\",\"app.kubernetes.io/name\":\"ray\",\"bench.ray.cluster\":\"ray\"},\"name\":\"ray-job-script\",\"namespace\":\"ray\"}}\n    creationTimestamp: \"2026-06-23T21:23:19Z\"\n    labels:\n      app.kubernetes.io/component: job-script\n      app.kubernetes.io/name: ray\n      bench.ray.cluster: ray\n    name: ray-job-script\n    namespace: ray\n    resourceVersion: \"914926\"\n    uid: c2ff02f9-3346-4b46-afe4-1107c3c8bc66\nkind: List\nmetadata:\n  resourceVersion: \"\"","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"85faf514-3d43-4993-aeb4-d5454267892f","uuid":"acd344a8-25cb-47ea-817d-0e8c3300c59e","timestamp":"2026-06-23T21:36:16.644Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"apiVersion: v1\nitems:\n- apiVersion: v1\n  data:\n    plan.md: |\n      # Ray Cluster Change / Migration Plan\n      ## Review Date: 2026-06-23\n      ## Status: DRAFT — NO CHANGES APPLIED\n\n      ---\n\n      ## 1. Current Cluster State\n\n      ### Namespace\n      - **Namespace:** `ray`\n\n      ### Deployments\n\n      | Deployment   | Replicas | Image                    | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |\n      |-------------|----------|--------------------------|-------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|\n      | ray-head    | 1        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0     | (none)      | (none)    | (none)         | (none)       |\n      | ray-worker  | 3        | rayproject/ray:2.9.0     | (none)      | (none)    | (none)         | (none)       |\n\n      ### Service: ray-head (ClusterIP)\n\n      | Port Name | Port  | Target Port | Protocol |\n      |-----------|-------|-------------|----------|\n      | gcs       | 6379  | 6379        | TCP      |\n      | dashboard | 8265  | 8265        | TCP      |\n      | client    | 10001 | 10001       | TCP      |\n\n      The dashboard port (8265) is exposed on the ClusterIP service — this is a\n      non-default addition beyond the minimal GCS port required for cluster operation.\n\n      ### Notable Observations\n      - Neither deployment has resource requests or limits set (`resources: {}`).\n        This means the pods are BestEffort QoS class and can be OOM-killed under\n        node pressure without warning.\n      - The cluster runs Ray 2.9.0, which is multiple minor versions behind the\n        current stable series.\n      - Workers were scaled from the default of 1 to 3 replicas, providing more\n        parallel task capaci